T1  - The Use of Modular Organizational Forms: An Industry-Level Analysis
AU  - Schilling, Melissa A.
AU  - Steensma, H. Kevin
Y1  - 2001/12/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069394
DO  - 10.5465/3069394
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1149
EP  - 1168
VL  - 44
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In many industries, integrated hierarchical organizations have been replaced by nonhierarchical entities that are permeable, interconnected, and modular. Other industries, however, maintain relatively high levels of integration. We use the logic of general systems modularity to explain why in some industries there is a greater use of modular organizational forms, including contract manufacturing, alternative work arrangements, and alliances, than in other industries. This model was tested using data from 330 U.S. manufacturing industries.
AB  - In many industries, integrated hierarchical organizations have been replaced by nonhierarchical entities that are permeable, interconnected, and modular. Other industries, however, maintain relatively high levels of integration. We use the logic of general systems modularity to explain why in some industries there is a greater use of modular organizational forms, including contract manufacturing, alternative work arrangements, and alliances, than in other industries. This model was tested using data from 330 U.S. manufacturing industries.
