TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Incident Command System: High-Reliability Organizing for Complex and Volatile Task Environments
AU  - Bigley, Gregory A.
AU  - Roberts, Karlene H.
Y1  - 2001/12/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069401
DO  - 10.5465/3069401
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1281
EP  - 1299
VL  - 44
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The incident command system (ICS) is a particular approach to assembly and control of the highly reliable temporary organizations employed by many public safety professionals to manage diverse resources at emergency scenes. Our inductive study of a fire department?s use of the ICS identified three main factors enabling this distinctively bureaucratic system to produce remarkably flexible and reliable organizations for complex, volatile task environments. This research suggests the possibility of new organizational forms able to capitalize on the control and efficiency benefits of bureaucracy while avoiding or overcoming its tendencies toward inertia.
AB  - The incident command system (ICS) is a particular approach to assembly and control of the highly reliable temporary organizations employed by many public safety professionals to manage diverse resources at emergency scenes. Our inductive study of a fire department?s use of the ICS identified three main factors enabling this distinctively bureaucratic system to produce remarkably flexible and reliable organizations for complex, volatile task environments. This research suggests the possibility of new organizational forms able to capitalize on the control and efficiency benefits of bureaucracy while avoiding or overcoming its tendencies toward inertia.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/3069401
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/3069401
